        <name>19.2.9.7 (NOT IN QUIZ) LR circuit ODE</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In an LR circuit with applied voltage \(E = {@g@}\), the current \(i\) is given by&lt;/p&gt;
\[L\frac{\mathrm{d}i}{\mathrm{d}t} + Ri = {@g@}.\]
&lt;p&gt;If the initial current is \(i_0\), find \(i\) subsequently.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(i(t) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;This is a linear differential equation that is not in standard form.&lt;/p&gt;
\[L\frac{\mathrm{d}i}{\mathrm{d}t} + Ri = {@g@}\]
&lt;p&gt;We must first convert it to standard form by dividing both sides by \(L\).
Note that here \(f(t) = R/L\) and \(\displaystyle g(t) = {@g / L@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}i}{\mathrm{d}t} + \frac{R}{L}i = {@g / L@}.\]
&lt;p&gt;We use the key point to find the integrating factor:&lt;/p&gt;
\[\text{I.F.} = \exp \left[ \int f(t) \,\mathrm{d}t \right] = {@IF@}\]
&lt;p&gt;Next we transform the equation into exact form by multiplying both sides with the
    integrating factor. It becomes:
&lt;/p&gt;
\[{@IF@} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d}i}{\mathrm{d}t} + \frac{R}{L} {@IF@} \cdot i = {@IF@} \cdot \left({@g / L@}\right)\]
&lt;p&gt;Note that the left-hand side is the derivative of \({@IF@} \cdot i\) with respect to \(t\).
    Our equation then becomes:
&lt;/p&gt;
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t} \left( {@IF@} \cdot i \right) = {@IF * g / L@}\]
&lt;p&gt;Therefore, we can find an expression for \({@IF@} \cdot i\) by integrating the right-hand side.
    The result is:
&lt;/p&gt;
\[{@IF@} \cdot i = {@I@}\]
&lt;p&gt;Which then gives the following general solution:&lt;/p&gt;
\[i = {@gsol@}\]
&lt;p&gt;We can now solve for \(C\) and use the given boundary conditions:&lt;/p&gt;
\[C = {@Cexp@}\]
\[i(0) = i_0 \implies C = {@C0@}\]
&lt;p&gt;This gives the particular solution we seek:&lt;/p&gt;
\[i(t) = {@ta@}\]</generalfeedback>
